Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.73,0:00:11.86,OP-ED,,0,0,0,,{\pos(633.333,305.333)}{\c&H00D8FF&\fs55\pos(960,340)}阿尔法小分队荣誉译制\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs45}{\c&H43DEAA&\fs45}翻：@ErrorEnvyEnchant 校：@ Auriance 压制：@Mihael_Ho \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs45}{\c&H00D8FF&\fs55}长期招募 详情见微博置顶@阿尔法小分队科教组
Dialogue: 0,0:00:06.73,0:00:09.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,大家好 我是凯莉·安 欢迎来到计算机科学速成课\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Hi, I'm Carrie Anne, and welcome to Crash Course Computer Science!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.06,0:00:13.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,前6集 我们深入研究了软件 从早期的编程工作\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Over the past six episodes, we delved into software, from early programming efforts to
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.00,0:00:15.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,到现代软件工程的实践\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}modern software engineering practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:15.20,0:00:19.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,50年里 软件的复杂度从手打在纸带上的机器码\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Within about 50 years, software grew in complexity from machine code punched by hand
Dialogue: 0,0:00:19.20,0:00:22.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,到面向对象的编程语言\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}onto paper tape, to object oriented programming languages,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.33,0:00:24.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,并在集成开发环境编译\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} compiled in integrated development environments.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.66,0:00:27.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是这个复杂度的增加离不开 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But this growth in sophistication would not have been possible
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.46,0:00:29.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,硬件的提高\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} without improvements in hardware.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.40,0:00:42.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,要理解计算机硬件的功率和复杂度的爆炸增长\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}To appreciate computing hardware's explosive growth in power and sophistication,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.26,0:00:45.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,要回到电子计算机的诞生时期\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}we need to go back to the birth of electronic computing.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.60,0:00:49.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,从大约1940年代到1960年代中期 每个电脑\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}From roughly the 1940's through the mid-1960s, every computer was built
Dialogue: 0,0:00:49.60,0:00:54.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,都是由单独的部分组成 叫做分立元件 全部由线连接\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}from individual parts, called discrete components, which were all wired together.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.13,0:00:59.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,比如 ENIAC计算机由超过17,000真空管70,000电阻器\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}For example, the ENIAC, consisted of more than 17,000 vacuum tubes, 70,000 resistors,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:59.06,0:01:01.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,10,000电容器和7,000二极管组成\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}10,000 capacitors, and 7,000 diodes,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.80,0:01:05.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这些需要5百万手工焊接\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} all of which required 5 million hand-soldered connections.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.60,0:01:09.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,增加元件提高性能意味着更多连接和线路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Adding more components to increase performance meant more connections, more wires,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.46,0:01:13.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,更加复杂  被戏称为数字暴政\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and just more complexity, what was dubbed the Tyranny of Numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.06,0:01:16.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1950年代中期 晶体管商业化成功\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By the mid 1950s, transistors were becoming commercially available
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.46,0:01:18.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,并装备进计算机\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} and being incorporated into computers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:18.46,0:01:22.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,他们比真空管更小更快更可靠\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}These were much smaller, faster and more reliable than vacuum tubes,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.20,0:01:25.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是每个晶体管仍是一个分立元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}but each transistor was still one discrete component.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:25.33,0:01:30.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1959年 IBM把709计算机升级\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In 1959, IBM upgraded their vacuum-tube-based “709” computers to transistors
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.73,0:01:34.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,将分立真空管替换为分立晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} by replacing all the discrete vacuum tubes with discrete transistors.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:34.40,0:01:39.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,新的计算机 IBM 7090是原来的6倍快 花费一半 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The new machine, the IBM 7090, was six times faster and half the cost.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.73,0:01:44.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这些晶体管计算机是电子计算机的第二代的标志\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}These transistorized computers marked the second generation of electronic computing.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.13,0:01:47.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是 尽管更快更小 分立晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}However, although faster and smaller, discrete transistors didn't
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.40,0:01:48.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,没有解决数字暴政\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}solve the Tyranny of Numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.93,0:01:52.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,设计起来更困难 更不用说实际制造计算机\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It was getting unwieldy to design, let alone physically manufacture computers
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.20,0:01:54.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,用到上千的独立组件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}with hundreds of thousands of individual components.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.53,0:01:57.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,到了1960年代 晶体管计算机到达了极限\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By the the 1960s, this was reaching a breaking point.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.40,0:02:00.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,计算机内部常常是大量缠绕的电线\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The insides of computers were often just huge tangles of wires.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.13,0:02:04.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,看看1965年的 PDP-8内部长什么样吧\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Just look at what the inside of a PDP-8 from 1965 looked like!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.13,0:02:06.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,答案是上升到新一层的抽象\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The answer was to bump up a new level of abstraction,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.66,0:02:08.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把内部复杂的结构包装起来\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and package up underlying complexity!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.66,0:02:12.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1958年有了突破 德州仪器的杰克·基尔比\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The breakthrough came in 1958, when Jack Kilby, working at Texas Instruments,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:12.93,0:02:15.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,展示了这样一个电子部件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}demonstrated such an electronic part,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.20,0:02:19.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,“这里所有的电子电路的部件都完全成为一体”\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} “wherein all the components of the electronic circuit are completely integrated.“
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.46,0:02:23.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,简单来说 不是用分离元件搭建计算机的部件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Put simply: instead of building computer parts out of many discrete components
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.20,0:02:26.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把它们连起来 把很多元件放在一起\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} and wiring them all together, you put many components together,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.33,0:02:28.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,放在一个新的单个元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} inside of a new, single component.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:28.33,0:02:31.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,它们叫做集成电路 简称IC\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}These are called Integrated Circuits, or ICs.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.13,0:02:34.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,同样在1959年几个月后 仙童半导体公司由罗伯特·诺伊斯\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}A few months later in 1959, Fairchild Semiconductor, lead by Robert Noyce,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.93,0:02:36.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,使IC能实用\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}made ICs practical.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.40,0:02:40.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,基尔比用锗这一稀有且不稳定的元素造IC\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Kilby built his ICs out of germanium, a rare and unstable material.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.80,0:02:43.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是 仙童公司使用大储量的硅\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But, Fairchild used the abundant silicon,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.26,0:02:45.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,占地壳的四分之一\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}which makes up about a quarter of the earth's crust!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.26,0:02:48.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,而且更加稳定 从而更加可靠\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It's also more stable, therefore more reliable.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.13,0:02:51.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,因此诺伊斯被认为是IC之父\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}For this reason, Noyce is widely regarded as the father of modern ICs,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.46,0:02:54.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,引领了电子时代 以及硅谷 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}ushering in the electronics era... and also Silicon Valley,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.86,0:02:58.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,仙童公司就建于此 随后许多其他半导体公司\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} where Fairchild was based and where many other semiconductor companies
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.00,0:02:58.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,迅速发展起来\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}would soon pop up.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.86,0:03:03.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,过去 一个IC可能只含有一个简单电路和几个晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In the early days, an IC might only contain a simple circuit with just a few transistors,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.13,0:03:05.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,例如这个西屋公司的\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}like this early Westinghouse example.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:05.13,0:03:08.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,即使这个IC也能使简单电路 如第3集的逻辑门\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But even this allowed simple circuits, like the logic gates from Episode 3,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.66,0:03:10.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,包装到一个单独部件中\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}to be packaged up into a single component.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.66,0:03:14.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,IC有点像 计算机工程师用来建造房屋的乐高\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}ICs are sort of like lego for computer engineers “building blocks” that can be arranged
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.33,0:03:16.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以被排列成无限可能的设计\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}into an infinite array of possible designs.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.33,0:03:20.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是 它们必要时仍然要用线连接\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}However, they still have to be wired together at some point to create even bigger
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.06,0:03:22.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,形成更复杂的电路 像是电脑\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and more complex circuits, like a whole computer.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.80,0:03:27.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,为此 工程师有了另一个创新：印刷电路板 简称PCB\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}For this, engineers had another innovation: printed circuit boards, or PCBs.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.13,0:03:30.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,不再焊接和捆绑不计其数的电线\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Instead of soldering and bundling up bazillions of wires,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.13,0:03:32.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,PCB可以大量生产\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}PCBs, which could be mass manufactured,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.13,0:03:36.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把所有金属线刻上来连接不同部件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} have all the metal wires etched right into them to connect components together.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:36.06,0:03:39.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,同时用到PCB和IC \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By using PCBs and ICs together, one could achieve exactly the same
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.86,0:03:42.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以实现分立元件相同功能的电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}functional circuit as that made from discrete components,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:42.46,0:03:45.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是远远更少的分立元件和缠绕的线\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}but with far fewer individual components and tangled wires.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.73,0:03:48.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,另外 它更便宜 更可靠\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Plus, it's smaller, cheaper and more reliable.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.40,0:03:49.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,三赢\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Triple win!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.60,0:03:53.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,许多早期IC用小的分立元件制作\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Many early ICs were manufactured using teeny tiny discrete components
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.00,0:03:57.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,包装形成一个单独的单元 像是这个IBM1964年的\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}packaged up as a single unit, like this IBM example from 1964.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.33,0:04:00.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是 即使使用非常非常小的元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}However, even when using really really itty-bitty components,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.66,0:04:04.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把超过5个晶体管装到一个IC上也是困难的\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} it was hard to get much more than around five transistors onto a single IC.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.40,0:04:08.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,为了完成更复杂的设计 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}To achieve more complex designs, a radically different fabrication process
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.26,0:04:11.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,需要完全不同的制作方法 光刻法\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}was needed that changed everything: Photolithography!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.06,0:04:15.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,简单来说 这个方法用光线把复杂的图案转移到一块材料上\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In short, it's a way to use light to transfer complex patterns to a material,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.20,0:04:16.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,像是半导体\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} like a semiconductor.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.66,0:04:19.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,只有基本的几个操作 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It only has a few basic operations, but these can be used
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.93,0:04:21.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,却可以创造非常复杂的电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}to create incredibly complex circuits.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.46,0:04:26.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,让我们过一遍简单但广泛的例子 制作一个电路 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Let's walk through a simple, although extensive example, to make one of these!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.00,0:04:30.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,从一片硅开始 像是一片薄饼干 叫做晶片\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We start with a slice of silicon, which, like a thin cookie, is called a wafer.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.06,0:04:31.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,美味\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Delicious!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.00,0:04:35.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,在第2集简单说过 硅的特殊在于它是半导体\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Silicon, as we discussed briefly in episode 2, is special because it's a semiconductor,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.06,0:04:39.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,半导体有时会传导电流 有时不会\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}that is, a material that can sometimes conduct electricity and other times does not.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:39.73,0:04:41.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们能控制什么位置什么时候通断\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We can control where and when this happens,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.73,0:04:44.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,硅成了完美的制造晶体管的原料\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}making Silicon the perfect raw material for making transistors.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:44.60,0:04:48.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们把晶片作为基底承接复杂金属电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We can also use a wafer as a base to lay down complex metal circuits,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.13,0:04:52.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,所以一切是集合的 完美适合制作 集成电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}so everything is integrated, perfect for... integrated circuits!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.53,0:04:55.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,下一步是加一层薄的氧化层在硅上面\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The next step is to add a thin oxide layer on top of the silicon,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.66,0:04:57.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,作为保护涂层\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} which acts as a protective coating.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.20,0:05:00.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,然后加上一种特殊的化学物质叫做光致抗蚀剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Then, we apply a special chemical called a photoresist.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.06,0:05:03.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,当曝露在光下 这个化学物质变得可溶\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}When exposed to light, the chemical changes, and becomes soluble,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.40,0:05:05.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可被一种特殊化学物质洗掉\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}so it can be washed away with a different special chemical.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.86,0:05:07.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,光致抗蚀剂本身没用\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Photoresists aren't very useful by themselves,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.93,0:05:11.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是跟光掩膜一起就很有用\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}but are super powerful when used in conjunction with a photomask.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.13,0:05:14.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,它像是一片照片的胶片 不过不是\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}This is just like a piece of photographic film, but instead of a photo of a hamster
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.86,0:05:18.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,一个仓鼠吃着玉米煎饼的照片 而是需要转移到晶体上的图案\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}eating a tiny burrito, it contains a pattern to be transferred onto the wafer.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.53,0:05:22.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把光掩膜放在晶片上 打开大功率灯\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We do this by putting a photomask over the wafer, and turning on a powerful light.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.53,0:05:25.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,膜挡住了灯光 光致抗溶剂不变\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Where the mask blocks the light, the photoresist is unchanged.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.53,0:05:28.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,光线照射的光致抗蚀剂会产生化学变化\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But where the light does hit the photoresist it changes chemically
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.93,0:05:32.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们只能洗去暴露在光下的光之抗蚀剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}which lets us wash away only the photoresist that was exposed to light,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.13,0:05:34.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,有选择地暴露氧化层\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}selectively revealing areas of our oxide layer.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.73,0:05:37.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在使用另一种特殊化学物质 通常是酸\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Now, by using another special chemical, often an acid,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.46,0:05:39.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以去除暴露的氧化层\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}we can remove any exposed oxide,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.26,0:05:42.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,然后蚀刻小洞一直到硅层\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and etch a little hole the entire way down to the raw silicon.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.33,0:05:45.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,注意光致抗蚀剂下面的氧化层是被保护的\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Note that the oxide layer under the photoresist is protected.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.60,0:05:47.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们用另一种特殊化学物质\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}To clean up, we use yet another special chemical
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.86,0:05:50.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,洗去残留的光之抗蚀剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}that washes away any remaining photoresist.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:50.26,0:05:53.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,没错 光刻法用到了许多特殊化学品\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Yep, there are a lot of special chemicals in photolithography,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.20,0:05:55.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,每一个都有专门的用途\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}each with a very specific function!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:55.60,0:05:59.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在我们再看看硅片 我们想设置只有暴露的部分\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}So now we can see the silicon again, we want to modify only the exposed areas
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.53,0:06:01.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,能传导电流\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}to better conduct electricity.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.13,0:06:04.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,为了实现 需要采用一步化学方法改变它 叫做显影\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}To do that, we need to change it chemically through a process called: doping.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.53,0:06:06.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我不在开玩笑\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}I'm not even going to make a joke.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:06.53,0:06:07.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们继续\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Let's move on.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.13,0:06:09.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,通常在高温气体下进行\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Most often this is done with a high temperature gas,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.60,0:06:12.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,类似磷 渗透到硅片的暴露区域\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} something like Phosphorus, which penetrates into the exposed area of silicon.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.60,0:06:14.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,从而改变电学性质性质\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}This alters its electrical properties.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.60,0:06:17.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们不涉及半导体的物理和化学原理\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We're not going to wade into the physics and chemistry of semiconductors,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.46,0:06:19.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,如果你感兴趣 描述栏里有\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} but if you're interested, there's a link in the description
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.73,0:06:22.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,Veritasium频道我们朋友德里克·穆勒的视频链接\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}to an excellent video by our friend Derek Muller from Veritasium.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.66,0:06:26.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是我们还需要几轮光刻才能造成一个晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But, we still need a few more rounds of photolithography to build a transistor.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.80,0:06:30.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,过程再次开始 首先加上氧化层\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The process essentially starts again, first by building up a fresh oxide layer
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.66,0:06:32.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,再覆盖上光致抗溶剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}which we coat in photoresist.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.66,0:06:35.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在我们用不同图案的光掩膜\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Now, we use a photomask with a new and different pattern,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.53,0:06:38.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以在显影区域上方开一个小窗户\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} allowing us to open a small window above the doped area.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.26,0:06:41.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,再一次 洗去残留的光致抗蚀剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Once again, we wash away remaining photoresist.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.26,0:06:45.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在我们显影 但用不同的气体\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Now we dope, and avoid telling a hilarious joke, again, but with a different gas
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.33,0:06:48.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把一部分硅转化成不同的形式\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}that converts part of the silicon into yet a different form.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.00,0:06:51.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,光刻法里时间对控制很重要\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Timing is super important in photolithography in order to control things
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.20,0:06:53.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,像是显影的扩散和刻蚀的深度\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} like doping diffusion and etch depth.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.20,0:06:57.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这里 我们只想在其他区域里显影一小块区域\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In this case, we only want to dope a little region nested inside the other.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.26,0:07:00.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在有了构建晶体管的所有部件了\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Now we have all the pieces we need to create our transistor!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.00,0:07:02.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,最后一步是在氧化层里打通道\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The final step is to make channels in the oxide layer
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.60,0:07:05.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这样就可以在晶体管不同部分排布小导线了\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}so that we can run little metal wires to different parts of our transistor.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.80,0:07:11.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,再次 覆盖光致抗蚀剂 用光掩膜 刻蚀更小的通道\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Once more, we apply a photoresist, and use a new photomask to etch little channels.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.20,0:07:13.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现在 用一个新的过程 叫金属化\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Now, we use a new process, called metalization,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.53,0:07:17.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们覆盖一层薄的金属 像是铝或铜\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}that allows us to deposit a thin layer of metal, like aluminium or copper.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.53,0:07:19.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是我们不想金属覆盖住所有\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But we don't want to cover everything in metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.53,0:07:21.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,而是刻出特定的电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}We want to etch a very specific circuit design.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.53,0:07:26.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,所以 跟前面相似 我们覆盖光致抗蚀剂\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}So, very similar to before, we apply a photoresist, use a photomask,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.26,0:07:30.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,溶解暴露的抗蚀剂 去除暴露的金属\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}dissolve the exposed resist, and use a chemical to remove any exposed metal.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.93,0:07:33.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,咻 我们的晶体管终于完成了\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Whew! Our transistor is finally complete!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.06,0:07:35.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,它有三个小导线连接连接硅片的不同部分\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It has three little wires that connect to three different parts of the silicon,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.93,0:07:38.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,每个显影特定的线路 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}each doped a particular way to create,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.73,0:07:41.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,形成了这里的双极型晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}in this example, what's called a bipolar junction transistor.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.60,0:07:46.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这是1962年真实的图案 它永久改变了我们的世界\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Here's the actual patent from 1962, an invention that changed our world forever!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.20,0:07:49.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,用相同的步骤 光刻法可以创造其他有用的电子元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Using similar steps, photolithography can create other useful electronic elements,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.93,0:07:53.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,像是电阻器和电容器 都在一块硅片上\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}like resistors and capacitors, all on a single piece of silicon
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.26,0:07:56.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,（加上连接成电路的导线）\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}(plus all the wires needed to hook them up into circuits).
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.20,0:07:57.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,再见分立元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Goodbye discrete components!
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.80,0:08:01.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这个例子里我们做了一个晶体管 实际上\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In our example, we made one transistor, but in the real world,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.20,0:08:03.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,光掩膜瞬间设置百万的细节\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}photomasks lay down millions of little details all at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:03.93,0:08:06.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这是IC从上面看的样子\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Here is what an IC might look like from above,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.06,0:08:08.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,导线上下彼此交叉\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} with wires crisscrossing above and below each other,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.66,0:08:12.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,连接所有独立的单元形成复杂的电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}interconnecting all the individual elements together into complex circuits.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.13,0:08:14.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,虽然我们可以制造整个基底的光掩膜\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Although we could create a photomask for an entire wafer,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.93,0:08:17.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,不过我们利用光的聚焦性质\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}we can take advantage of the fact that light can be focused
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.66,0:08:19.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,投影到我们想要的大小\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} and projected to any size we want.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.20,0:08:22.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,与电影胶片投影到整个荧幕相同\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In the same way that a film can be projected to fill an entire movie screen,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.26,0:08:25.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们可以把光掩膜聚焦到一块很小的硅上\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}we can focus a photomask onto a very small patch of silicon,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.73,0:08:28.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,创造非常精密的细节\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} creating incredibly fine details.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.33,0:08:31.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,一个硅晶片通常可以制作几十个IC\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}A single silicon wafer is generally used to create dozens of ICs.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.26,0:08:34.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,当一整个晶片填满了 切开\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Then, once you've got a whole wafer full, you cut them up and package them
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.26,0:08:38.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,并包装成微型芯片 就是那种你在电子产品中常见的黑色小矩形\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}into microchips, those little black rectangles you see in electronics all the time.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:38.40,0:08:40.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,记住：那些芯片的核心\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Just remember: at the heart of each of those chips
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.86,0:08:42.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,都是这些小的硅片\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}is one of these small pieces of silicon.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.26,0:08:45.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,随着光刻技术的进步 晶体管的尺寸缩小了\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}As photolithography techniques improved, the size of transistors shrunk,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.73,0:08:47.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,密度更大\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}allowing for greater densities.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.33,0:08:51.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1960年代初期一个IC很少超过5个晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}At the start of the 1960s, an IC rarely contained more than 5 transistors,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.93,0:08:53.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,不可能放得下\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} they just couldn't possibly fit.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.33,0:08:55.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是到了1960年代中期 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But, by the mid 1960s,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.33,0:08:58.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,市面上开始有了超过100个晶体管的IC\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} we were starting to see ICs with over 100 transistors on the market.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.66,0:09:02.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1965年 戈登·摩尔看到了趋势：大约每两年\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In 1965, Gordon Moore could see the trend: that approximately every two years,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.66,0:09:04.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,得益于材料和制造技术的进步\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} thanks to advances in materials and manufacturing,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.93,0:09:08.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以在同样的空间内装两倍的晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}you could fit twice the number of transistors into the same amount of space.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:08.80,0:09:10.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这叫摩尔定律\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}This is called Moore's Law.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.80,0:09:12.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但是这个定律有点错误\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The term is a bit of a misnomer though.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.40,0:09:14.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,他并不是真正的定律 更像是趋势\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It's not really a law at all, more of a trend.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:14.40,0:09:15.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,但很准确\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But it's a good one.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.33,0:09:22.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,IC价格也巨幅下降 从平均1962年平均50刀到1968年2刀\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}IC prices also fell dramatically, from an average of $50 in 1962 to around $2 in 1968.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.40,0:09:24.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,今天 你可以只花几分钱买到IC\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Today, you can buy ICs for cents.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.40,0:09:27.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,更小的晶体管和更高的密度还有别的优点\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Smaller transistors and higher densities had other benefits too.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.53,0:09:30.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,更小的晶体管需要更少的电量驱动\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The smaller the transistor, the less charge you have to move around,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.80,0:09:33.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可以更快的切换状态并消耗更少能量\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}allowing it to switch states faster and consume less power.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.60,0:09:37.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,另外 更紧凑的电路意味着更少的信号延迟从而加快时钟频率\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Plus, more compact circuits meant less delay in signals resulting in faster clock speeds.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.93,0:09:42.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1968年 罗伯特·诺伊斯和戈登·摩尔合作成立了一个新的公司\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In 1968, Robert Noyce and Gordon Moore teamed up and founded a new company,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:42.20,0:09:47.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,把集成和电子两个词合并成Intel 今天最大的芯片制造商\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}combining the words Integrated and Electronics...Intel... the largest chip maker today.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.40,0:09:52.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,第7和8集的Intel 4004 CPU是一个巨大的里程碑\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The Intel 4004 CPU, from Episodes 7 and 8, was a major milestone.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.53,0:09:56.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,发行于1971年 是第一个上市的IC处理器\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Released in 1971, it was the first processor that shipped as an IC,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.53,0:10:00.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,它被叫做微型处理器 因为它真的很小\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}what's called a microprocessor, because it was so beautifully small!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.33,0:10:02.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,它含有2,300个晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}It contained 2,300 transistors.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.66,0:10:06.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,人们惊叹于集成的水平高到把一整个CPU放进一个芯片\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}People marveled at the level of integration, an entire CPU in one chip,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.73,0:10:10.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,而20年前会占满整个屋子\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}which just two decades earlier would have filled an entire room
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.06,0:10:11.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,当时用分立元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} using discrete components.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.40,0:10:15.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,集成电路尤其是微处理器的时代\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}This era of integrated circuits, especially microprocessors,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.06,0:10:17.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,引领了第三代计算\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}ushered in the third generation of computing.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:17.00,0:10:19.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,而Intel 4004就是开始\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}And the Intel 4004 was just the start.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:19.93,0:10:22.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,CPU的晶体管数量爆炸增长\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}CPU transistor count exploded!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:22.60,0:10:26.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,到了1980年 CPU有3万晶体管 \N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By 1980, CPUs contained 30 thousand transistors.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.66,0:10:30.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1990年 突破了1百万\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By 1990, CPUs breached the 1 million transistor count.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.33,0:10:33.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,2000年 3千万\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}By 2000, 30 million transistors,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.13,0:10:39.06,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,2010年 10亿 哦买噶\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} and by 2010, ONE BILLION TRANSISTORS IN ONE IC. OMG!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.06,0:10:43.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,为了达到这个密度 光刻法最细可能分辨率\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}To achieve this density, the finest resolution possible with photolithography
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.60,0:10:46.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,从1万纳米\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}has improved from roughly 10 thousand nanometers,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.13,0:10:48.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,即十分之一发丝厚度 提升到\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} that's about 1/10th the thickness of a human hair,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:48.66,0:10:50.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,今天14纳米\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}to around 14 nanometers today.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.86,0:10:53.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,比红细胞还小400倍\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}That's over 400 times smaller than a red blood cell!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.33,0:10:56.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,当然 CPU不是唯一受益的元件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}And of course, CPU's weren't the only components to benefit.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.00,0:10:58.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,绝大多数电子产品 以指数进步\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Most electronics advanced essentially exponentially:
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.93,0:11:03.00,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,RAM 显卡 固态硬盘 相机传感器 等等\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}RAM, graphics cards, solid state hard drives, camera sensors, you name it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.00,0:11:06.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,今天的处理器 像是iPhone 7里的A10 CPU\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Today's processors, like the A10 CPU inside Of an iPhone 7,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.40,0:11:12.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,在1cm×1cm的大小的IC里竟然含有33亿晶体管\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}contains a mind melting 3.3 BILLION transistors in an IC roughly 1cm by 1cm.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.53,0:11:14.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,比一张邮票还小\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}That's smaller than a postage stamp!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.46,0:11:16.80,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,现代工程师并不是手工设计\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}And modern engineers aren't laying out these designs by hand,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.80,0:11:19.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,一次放一个 人工不可能\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}one transistor at a time - it's not humanly possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.40,0:11:24.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1970年代超大尺寸集成软件 简称VLSI软件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Starting in the 1970's, very-large-scale integration, or VLSI software,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.73,0:11:27.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,被用于自动生产芯片设计\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}has been used to automatically generate chip designs instead.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.40,0:11:30.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,使用逻辑综合技术布置整个的高级部件\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Using techniques like logic synthesis, where whole, high-level components
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.86,0:11:33.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,像是缓存\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} can be laid down, like a memory cache,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:33.20,0:11:35.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这个软件最高效地产生电路\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}the software generates the circuit in the most efficient way possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.60,0:11:39.20,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,很多人认为这是计算机第四代的开始\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Many consider this to be the start of fourth generation computers.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.20,0:11:42.73,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,不幸的是 专家预计摩尔定律将在几十年内结束\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Unfortunately, experts have been predicting the end of Moore's Law for decades,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:42.73,0:11:44.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我们可能很接近了\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and we might finally be getting close to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.40,0:11:48.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,进一步缩小有两个大问题\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}There are two significant issues holding us back from further miniaturization.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:48.13,0:11:51.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,首先 我们达到了光掩膜上的图案分辨率的极限\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}First, we're bumping into limits on how fine we can make features on a photomask
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.93,0:11:55.86,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,光刻发用的光的波长导致了晶片\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}and it's resultant wafer due to the wavelengths of light used in photolithography.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.86,0:11:58.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,为了应对 科学家开发光源\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}In response, scientists have been developing light sources
Dialogue: 0,0:11:58.53,0:12:02.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,的波长越来越短 从而投影更小的图案\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}with smaller and smaller wavelengths that can project smaller and smaller features.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.60,0:12:05.46,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,第二个问题是晶体管越来越小\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}The second issue is that when transistors get really really small,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.46,0:12:08.26,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,这样电极可能只被几十个原子分隔\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40} where electrodes might be separated by only a few dozen atoms,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.26,0:12:12.13,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,电子可以越过这个间隔 这一现象叫做量子隧穿\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}electrons can jump the gap, a phenomenon called quantum tunneling.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.13,0:12:15.33,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,如果晶体管泄露电流 就不是合格的开关\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}If transistors leak current, they don't make very good switches.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.33,0:12:17.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,尽管如此 科学家和工程师努力\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Nonetheless, scientists and engineers are hard at work
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.53,0:12:19.53,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,寻找解决方法\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}figuring out ways around these problems.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.53,0:12:23.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,1nm的晶体管已经在实验室展示出来\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Transistors as small as 1 nanometer have been demonstrated in research labs.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:23.40,0:12:27.40,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,是否将来能商业化仍是个谜\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}Whether this will ever be commercially feasible remains MASKED in mystery.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.40,0:12:29.66,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,可能将来会解决\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}But maybe we'll be able to RESOLVE it in the future.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.66,0:12:30.93,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,我很想知道\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}I'm dying to know.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:30.93,0:12:32.60,720P-CN,,0,0,0,,下周见\N{\c&H00D8FF&\fs40}See you next week.
